snippet.textDisplay:
This ISN’T OCD. OCD is a serious mental illness that the World Health Organisation ranks in the Top 20 most debillitating diseases. It pissed me the hell off to see these absolute MORONS fuelling stigma and nonsense.

This therapist is also NOT a psychologist. I’d like to see her qualifications. OCD is an anxiety disorder that’s ‘ego-dystonic’, in that it causes distress and puts the sufferer OUTSIDE of a comfortable state. First, there’s the ‘obsession’, or intrusive thought, which is a belief about harm or danger (ie, ‘my family will get badly hurt if I don’t....’, or ‘I will hurt someone if I...’ or ‘I will get sick if....’) and then there’s the compulsion, which is the action that immediately but artificially reduces the anxiety brought on by the intrusive thought (ie checking that the door is locked twenty five times, tapping out a very specific rhythm on every different surface and wall around you, or washing your hands repetitively)

Liking your things in order isn’t OCD unless the order is to prevent something bad happening. Liking things in order is ego-syntotic: it is aligned with the ego state. It isn’t to prevent something bad happening, it just fits with a person’s character, for example because they’re clean or tidy. It isn’t OCD unless it causes you serious mental distress, severe anxiety and panic if things get moved out of that order. Exposure Therapy is for anxiety disorders. To ‘experiment’ on a healthy person for clout on a TV show with a therapeutic model is not ethical.

Thank you for coming to my TED talk. Now f*** all the way off with this bull****. And don’t none of y’all who read this ever use ‘OCD’ in an out of context way again, unless you want to be cursed with the real thing.
